value.0: Fashioned from rough-hewn wood, this simple door swings on ill-fitting hinges.

These leaves are cut up, then boiled in hog's fat.  The sediment strained from the mixture makes an ointment used to promote healing.

Effect: 1d2 hit points regained immediately and 1d3 hit points regained during your next period of rest.

The flowers of this plant are soaked in wine to make an oil used to close wounds and heal bruises.

Effect: 1d4 hit points regained and saving throw vs. poison boosted for 2 turns.

A lotion made from this plant's roots and leaves can be applied to boils, abrasions, insect bites, splinters, minor wounds, and skin problems.

Effect: 1d4 + 1hit points regained.

The sap from this plant is applied to burns in order to produce quick healing.

Effect: 1d2 hit points regained immediately and 1d2 hit points regained during your next period of rest.

This white flowering plant has black seeds and roots with a sharp taste. 
The root, when brewed, makes a hot, peppery decoction that helps
alleviate common colds, flu and congestions

The flowers of this plant are dried, boiled and strained, then mixed with fat to produce an ointment useful for treating bruises and sprains.

Effect: 1d3 temporary hit points gained for 1d2 + 1 hours.

Attanar is a moss, which when applied to the forehead of a stricken
person, will cure fevers.

A small succulent that, when crushed, tends to repel parasitic insects,
including mosquitoes and the like. It has a pungent but not unpleasant
odour.  The scent lingers for several hours, but can be washed off.

Eating bilberries will cure sight problems.

Effect: Remove blindness.

These seeds are chewed as a stimulant.

Effect: +1 to listen, search and spot for 1d2 hours.

The leaves of this plant are applied to poisonous wounds and stings, lessening the chance of a long-term infection.

Effect: +2 bonus to saving throws vs. poison for two hours.  1d2 hit points recovered during your next period of rest.

The leaves from this plant are mashed and boiled, then applied to cuts, sores, burns, and frostbite in order to soothe pain.

Effect: 1d4 hit points recovered immediately, and 3 hit points recovered during your next period of rest.

The flowers from this plant are rubbed over the body to irritate insects, driving the common varieties away and causing giant varieties to be weakened upon contact with the user.

Effect: +2 natural armor bonus vs. vermin for 2d4 hours.

Cassil is a small shrub similar to a mustard plant. Its seeds are ground into a fine, tasteless powder that supresses male fertility. Men who want to avoid fathering children use this herb. A male humanoid who eats about a teaspoon of this herb is rendered infertile for a period of 3d4 days, although it requires about an hour for this herb to take effect. 

Stories abound of disloyal courtiers dosing their lords in order to prevent the conception of an heir.

The leaves of this plant, when used, helps the user prevent infections for a duration of time.

Effect: Saving throws vs. disease increased by 2 for one day.

Though it takes some time to take effect, the leaves of this plant, when consumed, will aid the healing process.

Effect: 1d4 hit points recovered immediately, and an additional 1d3 hit points recovered during your next period of rest.

These leaves are a very powerful insect repellant, causing even magically-summoned insects to shy away.  Giant insects are reluctant to attack someone who has been treated with these leaves.

Effect: +3 Natural armor bonus vs. vermin and immunity to the spell "Creeping Doom" for 2d4 hours.

These odd leaves are rubbed on the eyes.  Though they cause temporary blindness, they also allow the user to see invisible, astral, ethereal, or illusory objects as if they were real.

Effect: Blindness and True Seeing for 2d10 rounds.

This plant can be rubbed into wounds or sore muscles as a curative.

Effect: 1d3 + 2 hit points recovered immediately.

When applied to a patient's cysts, boils, or other infections, this plant will slowly cause the infections to recede.

Effect: Remove skin infection-type diseases.

These flowers are used to cure various diseases, but causes a euphoric feeling that makes him not-so-capable in battle.

Effect: -2 to all actions for 1d4 hours.  Cures fever-type diseases.

Leaves of the fiendflower plant, when consumed, cause the user to suffer an episode of horrifying hallucinations. 

Effect: Confusion for 2d6 rounds.

A paste or lotion from this plant will aid healing, causing the user to slowly recover from injuries.

Effect: 1d4 + 1 hit points recovered during your next night's rest.

This root is repulsive to all types of undead creatures, causing many to stay away from the user.

Effect: +2 Natural Armor bonus vs. undead for 2d4 hours.

Leaves of the Ginkgo are consumed in order to enhance the memory for an amount of time.

Effect: +1 to intelligence and wisdom-based skill checks for 2d4 hours.

This root is consumed in order to give energy to the user.  It also serves as an aphrodesiac.

Effect: +1 to strength and dexterity-based skill checks for 2d4 hours..

The leaves of this plant are dried and compacted into a pill form.  They are often used by wizards who wish to boost their intelligence, though they can cause painful side effects.

Effect: 1d4 damage, -1 to AC versus piercing and slashing damage, 1d4 + 1 intelligence bonus for 1d10 + 15 rounds.

These seeds make an excellent painkiller; however, they also are known to cause strange hallucinations.

Effect: 1d6 hit points gained, but -4 to all actions for two hours.  All but 2 of the hit points gained vanish after two hours.

Made from a special mixture of grapes, fruits, and herbs, this brew is usually given to captives engaged in hard labor in order to increase their strength while dulling their minds.

Effect: Wisdom -1, Saving Throws vs. Fear -20, Concentration -20, Discipline -20, Strength +2 for 1d3 turns.

These berries are a very powerful stimulant.  Someone on the brink of death can be healed if forced to consume them.

Effect: 1d4 hit points healed for a target who has fallen below zero hit points, and +1 to saving throws vs. poison for two hours.

Nararoot is a black, woody tuber with a licoricelike flavor. Shavings steeped in hot water make a strong tea that renders a woman infertile for 1d4+2 days. Chewed raw, the root tastes unpleasant, but the effects are more potent, lasting 2d4+4 days. Women who do not wish to become pregnant use nararoot.

The pouch contains 10 doses.

The berries of this plant are used to calm the mind, helping those suffereing from hysteria or fright.

Effect: Forces someone into a deep sleep.

These roots, when consumed, help to ward off the chance of contracting a disease.

Effect: +4 to saving throws vs. disease for 1d4 turns.

This root, when chewed, increases vitality.

Effect: -1d4 wisdom, +1d8 hit points for 10 rounds.

This fat red leaf releases a milky juice when chewed.  The juice is analgesic, and is often used by people suffering from extreme or chronic pain.

Effect: Damage reduction 1/+1, All saving throws +1, Dexterity -3 for 1d4 rounds.

When rubbed on the body, these leaves provide protection from cold equivalent to a heavy wool cloak.

Effect: +1 to saving throws vs. cold for 1d4 hours.

An oil made from the bark of this plant can be applied to wounds, healing damages from bruises or sprains.

Effect: 2d3 hit points recovered immediately.

In the absence of a priest or paladin, adventurers will pour just about anything down an open wound.  This balm made from wood alcohol is one of the few substances that is beneficial to apply to an injury.

Flowers from this plant are mixed with water or wine and applied to a wound to deaden the pain from injury.

Effect: 1d4 temporary hit points gained for two hours.

Rubbing this stinky green paste into wounds promotes rapid healing. Applying the salve is a full-round action. One dose cures 1d8 points of damage to a living creature. Only one dose may be applied per round, and there is no limit on how many salves can be applied over time.

Rubbing this stinky green paste into wounds promotes rapid healing. Applying the salve is a full-round action. One dose cures 1d8 points of damage to a living creature. Only one dose may be applied per round, and there is no limit on how many salves can be applied over time.
